commit d1468bf02144742dd92642ea126e9aac9c0fc19b
Author: Liew Rui Yan <aethernet65535@gmail.com>

mm/damon/lru_sort: add synchronous validation for commit_inputs

This commit adds a sysfs store function for the commit_inputs parameter in
DAMON's lru_sort module. It attempts to synchronously validate the module
parameters before setting the flag, providing immediate feedback instead of
failing silently in the background thread.

Link: https://lore.kernel.org/20260319151528.86490-1-sj@kernel.org

> diff --git a/mm/damon/lru_sort.c b/mm/damon/lru_sort.c
> index 554559d72976..0e5f9d29e294 100644
> --- a/mm/damon/lru_sort.c
> +++ b/mm/damon/lru_sort.c
[ ... ]
> @@ -361,6 +360,69 @@ static int damon_lru_sort_handle_commit_inputs(void)
>  	return err;
>  }
>  
> +/* Source: mm/damon/core.c */
> +static bool damon_valid_intervals_goal(struct damon_attrs *attrs)

Would it be better to export these generic validation functions from the core
DAMON subsystem (e.g., in include/linux/damon.h) instead of duplicating them
here?

If the core subsystem updates its validation rules or integer overflow
protections in the future, this duplicated copy could fall out of sync,
allowing the sysfs interface to synchronously accept parameters that the core
later rejects.

[ ... ]
> +static int damon_valid_attrs(struct damon_attrs *attrs)
> +{
> +	if (!damon_valid_intervals_goal(attrs))
> +		return -EINVAL;
> +	if (attrs->min_nr_regions < 3)
> +		return -EINVAL;
> +	if (attrs->min_nr_regions > attrs->max_nr_regions)
> +		return -EINVAL;
> +	if (attrs->sample_interval > attrs->aggr_interval)
> +		return -EINVAL;
> +
> +	return 0;
> +}

Is this validation missing the check for a zero sample interval?

The original asynchronous logic explicitly checks for this:

mm/damon/lru_sort.c:damon_lru_sort_apply_parameters() {
        ...
        if (!damon_lru_sort_mon_attrs.sample_interval) {
                err = -EINVAL;
                goto out;
        }
        ...
}

Without this check in the new synchronous path, a user configuring a sample
interval of 0 will pass validation here but still fail silently in the
background thread, defeating the purpose of the immediate feedback.

> +static int damon_lru_sort_commit_inputs_store(const char *val,
> +		const struct kernel_param *kp)
> +{
> +	struct damon_attrs attrs;
> +	bool yes;
> +	int err;
> +
> +	err = kstrtobool(val, &yes);
> +	if (err)
> +		return err;
> +
> +	if (commit_inputs == yes)
> +		return 0;
> +
> +	if (!yes)
> +		return 0;

Does this prevent users from clearing a pending commit?

If a user writes 'N' or '0', the function returns success immediately without
updating the commit_inputs state. This means if commit_inputs was previously
set to 'Y', the user cannot cancel it before the kdamond background thread
processes it.

> +
> +	attrs = damon_lru_sort_mon_attrs;
> +	err = damon_valid_attrs(&attrs);

Can this falsely reject valid configurations when autotune_monitoring_intervals
is enabled?

The asynchronous application function automatically overwrites the user-provided
sample_interval and aggr_interval with valid default values when autotuning
is active:

mm/damon/lru_sort.c:damon_lru_sort_apply_parameters() {
        ...
        attrs = damon_lru_sort_mon_attrs;
        if (autotune_monitoring_intervals) {
                attrs.sample_interval = 5000;
                attrs.aggr_interval = 100000;
                ...
        }
        ...
}

Running the static validation on the raw attributes before these overrides are
considered might return -EINVAL incorrectly, breaking configurations that would
have successfully applied using the autotune feature.

> +	if (err)
> +		return err;
> +
> +	commit_inputs = yes;
> +	return err;
> +}

